ica's smallholder farmers and present the concepts and practices of Sustainable Intensification (SI) as opportunities to sustainably transform Africa's agriculture sector and the livelihoods of millions of smallholders. The way forward, they write, will be an agriculture sector deeply rooted within SI: producing more with less, using fertilizers and pesticides more prudently, adapting to climate change, improving natural capital, adopting new technologies, and building resilience at every stage of the agriculture value chain.Food for All in Africa envisions a virtuous circle generated through agricultural development rooted in SI that results in greater yields, healthier diets, improved livelihoods for farmers, and sustainable economic opportunities for the rural poor that in turn generate further investment. It describes the benefits of digital technologies for farmers and the challenges of transforming African agricultural policies and creating effective and inspiring leadership.Food for All in Africa demonstrates why we should take on the challenge and provides ideas and methods through which it can be met.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAgricultural intensificationzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aAgricultural intensificationzAfrica. 0aFarms, SmallzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aFarms, SmallzAfrica. 0aFood securityzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aFood securityzAfrica. 0aProduce tradezAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aProduce tradezAfrica. 0aSustainable agriculturezAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aSustainable agriculturezAfrica. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aAgriculture. 4aGeneral Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  asustainable agriculture, resilience, value chains, hunger, malnutrition.1 aAdesina, Akinwumi A., econtributor.4ctb